{"id":"1912.07387","submitter":"Micha{\\l} Lipka","authors":"Micha{\\l} Lipka, Marcin Jarzyna, and Konrad Banaszek","title":"Quantum Fingerprinting over AWGN Channels with Power-Limited Optical\n  Signals","comments":null,"journal-ref":"in IEEE Journal on Selected Areas in Communications, vol. 38, no.\n  3, pp. 496-505, March 2020","doi":"10.1109/JSAC.2020.2968996","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum fingerprinting reduces communication complexity of determination\nwhether two $n$-bit long inputs are equal or different in the simultaneous\nmessage passing model. Here we quantify the advantage of quantum fingerprinting\nover classical protocols when communication is carried out using optical\nsignals with limited power and unrestricted bandwidth propagating over additive\nwhite Gaussian noise (AWGN) channels with power spectral density (PSD) much\nless than one photon per unit time and unit bandwidth. We identify a noise\nparameter whose order of magnitude separates near-noiseless quantum\nfingerprinting, with signal duration effectively independent of $n$, from a\nregime where the impact of AWGN is significant. In the latter case the signal\nduration is found to scale as $O(\\sqrt{n})$, analogously to classical\nfingerprinting. However, the dependence of the signal duration on the AWGN PSD\nis starkly distinct, leading to quantum advantage in the form of a reduced\nmultiplicative factor in $O(\\sqrt{n})$ scaling.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 16 Dec 2019 14:14:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 3 Apr 2020 09:48:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-06"}
